\f0\b\fs24 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
TF = Tully\'96Fisher relation
\f1\b0 , the spiral-galaxy analog of the Fundamental Plane. Discovered by 
\f0\b R. Brent Tully and J. Richard Fisher in 1977
\f1\b0  (
\f2\i A&A
\f1\i0  54, 661) \'97 it's the older and arguably more famous of the two, with nearly five decades of use as the workhorse distance indicator for spirals.\

\f0\b The core relation in one breath:
\f1\b0  the 
\f0\b luminosity
\f1\b0  of a spiral galaxy correlates tightly with its 
\f0\b rotational velocity
\f1\b0 :\
$$L \\propto V_\{\\rm rot\}^\{\\alpha\}$$\
where the slope $\\alpha$ depends on the photometric band \'97 historically ~3 in B-band, steepening to ~3.5\'964 in the near-IR (where it's tightest). Equivalently, in magnitude form:\
$$M = a \\log W + b$$\
with $W$ being the H I 21 cm line width (which directly traces $2 V_\{\\rm rot\} \\sin i$). Calibrate the slope $a$ and zero point $b$ on galaxies of known distance, then for any other spiral with measurable $W$ and apparent magnitude, compute $M$ from $W$, and the distance modulus drops out.\

\f0\b Why the relation exists physically:
\f1\b0  Hand-wavy version starts from virial equilibrium plus the assumption that spirals form a near-homologous family. For a self-gravitating disk in equilibrium, $V^2 \\sim GM/R$. If mass-to-light ratio $M/L$ is roughly constant and surface brightness is roughly constant across the spiral sequence (a reasonable approximation), you get $L \\propto V^4$ \'97 the Tully\'96Fisher relation in the near-IR is essentially the "baryonic Tully\'96Fisher" prediction once you swap luminosity for stellar mass.\
The deeper version invokes the 
\f0\b dark matter halo connection
\f1\b0 : $V_\{\\rm rot\}$ at large radii is set by the halo, while $L$ is set by the baryons. The remarkable tightness of TF (~0.3 mag scatter in the IR, ~0.5 mag in B) tells you that baryonic mass and halo mass are linked by a near-deterministic function across galaxies \'97 one of the empirical pillars of the modern galaxy formation framework.\

\f0\b Practical procedure:
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Imaging
\f1\b0  \'97 get optical or (better) near-IR photometry of the target spiral. Measure total apparent magnitude and the 
\f0\b inclination
\f1\b0  $i$ from axis ratio.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
H I observation
\f1\b0  \'97 get a 21 cm spectrum (single-dish like Arecibo/GBT, or interferometric like ALFALFA/WALLABY). Measure the line width $W_\{50\}$ (width at 50% of peak) or $W_\{20\}$ (at 20%).\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Inclination correction
\f1\b0  \'97 divide the observed line width by $\\sin i$ to recover $2 V_\{\\rm rot\}$.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Internal extinction correction
\f1\b0  \'97 correct apparent magnitude for dust within the galaxy (depends on inclination and morphology).\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
K-correction and Galactic extinction
\f1\b0  \'97 standard.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	6	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Plug corrected magnitude and corrected line width into the calibrated TF relation; read off distance modulus.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 Strengths for cosmology:
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Reaches huge samples cheaply.
\f1\b0  H I observations and optical/IR photometry are widely available; you can build catalogs of tens of thousands of galaxies. CF4's TF subset has ~10,000.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Spirals are everywhere.
\f1\b0  Unlike ellipticals (which cluster preferentially in dense environments), spirals populate field, group, and outer-cluster environments uniformly \'97 TF samples the velocity field where peculiar velocities are smaller and more representative.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Each measurement is cheap
\f1\b0  \'97 a 21 cm detection plus a single image is enough; you don't need spectroscopic resolution to get $\\sigma$ like in FP.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Reaches into the Hubble flow.
\f1\b0  TF works out to ~15,000 km/s with H I (with the inevitable selection bias toward H I-rich galaxies at large distance).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 Weaknesses:
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
~15\'9620% per-galaxy distance scatter
\f1\b0  \'97 much larger than SN Ia, so you need large samples.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Inclination is the dominant nuisance parameter.
\f1\b0  Face-on galaxies ($\\sin i \\to 0$) produce divergent corrections to line width; nearly edge-on galaxies are easier on the velocity correction but harder on the dust correction. Both extremes are usually thrown out, costing sample size.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Calibration zero-point is everything
\f1\b0 , just like FP. Calibrators are TF galaxies with independent distances from Cepheids, TRGB, or SBF. Differences in which calibrator set you use shift the zero-point at the ~few-percent level \'97 and you saw this propagate in our earlier CF4 discussion (Kourkchi+20 vs Tully+23 vs Boubel+24, all using essentially the same TF data).\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Malmquist bias
\f1\b0  is severe at the magnitude-limited end \'97 at large distances you see only the brightest spirals, biasing the distance estimates toward small values unless carefully corrected.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
H I selection bias.
\f1\b0  Quenched or H I\'96poor spirals (especially in cluster cores) drop out of TF samples; this distorts the mapping from "spirals" to "the velocity field."\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 Where TF lives in the H0DN figure:
\f1\b0 \
TF is the long, cheap pipeline from anchors all the way out to ~15,000 km/s, calibrated by a handful of nearby spirals with Cepheid or TRGB distances. It's primarily a third-rung tracer like FP, but the 
\f2\i much larger
\f1\i0  sample makes it the dominant source of statistical leverage in the Hubble-flow regime. The H0DN figure shows TF feeding from above (Cepheid + TRGB calibrators) and connecting outward to the largest velocity volumes.\

\f0\b The TF\'96FP complementarity:
\f1\b0 \
The two methods are best understood as a matched pair:\

